properties.Title: Weather Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Winter Weather Travel Advisory in effect for tonight into Thursday morning. Lake effect snow bands are expected to intensify overnight with local snowfall accumulations of 5 to 10 cm possible by Thursday morning. Gusty northwest winds could also lead to local blowing snow with these bands. Motorists should be prepared for quickly changing and deteriorating driving conditions through the night. The morning commute may also be impacted. The snow squalls will begin to weaken Thursday morning, with additional accumulations of 2 to 4 cm possible by Thursday afternoon. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
Expires: 2019-12-05T19:01:01-00:00

properties.Title: Update: High Water Advisory Alert Is Being Issued For The Roseau River From Gardenton To Dominion City
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for the Roseau River from Gardenton to Dominion City due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-12-05T12:30:00-06:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization, 2019-12-04T12:32:24-06:00, 179D94AF-83C2-D77A-4EC4-C03C8B6F5932
Area: Roseau River from Gardenton to Dominion City

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A long period of snowfall with total amounts of about 20 cm is expected. A low pressure centre over the Gulf of Alaska will bring heavy snow to the South Klondike Highway - Carcross to White Pass. The snow will begin Thursday morning and will continue Thursday night before tapering to a few flurries Friday morning. The highest snowfall amounts are expected near White Pass where 20 cm of snow is forecast by Friday morning ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Long-lasting blizzard conditions, with near zero visibility in snow and blowing snow, are expected to develop this evening. Although the visibility may improve at times, the hazardous conditions are forecast to continue into Friday. ### Travel is expected to be extremely hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NTStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls possible tonight into Thursday morning. Lake effect snow is expected through the day with local snowfall accumulations of 2 to 5 cm possible by this evening. As colder air moves over Lake Huron late in the afternoon, snow squalls are likely to affect the area beginning this evening. Local snowfall accumulations may reach 10 to 15 cm by Thursday morning in the heaviest snow squalls. Gusty northwest winds will also lead to local blowing snow with these snow squalls. The snow squalls will begin to weaken Thursday morning, with additional accumulations of 2 to 4 cm possible by Thursday afternoon. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Travel may be hazardous due to sudden changes in the weather. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
